quran[7]{c,v,t,f}:
  18,28,"And keep<a class=""sup""><sup>sg </sup></a>yourself patient in the company of those who pray to their Lord morning and evening, seeking His Countenance{1}, and do not turn your eyes away from them, seeking the adornment of the Earlier Life, and do not obey one whose heart We have made heedless of Our remembrance{2}so that he has followed his own whim and his affairs have become confused.",footnotes:1:Al-Alousi and other exegetes interpreted this expression as ‘to please Him’.The Arabic word zhikrcan be translated as ‘remembrance’, ‘reminder’ or ‘mentioning’.
  18,29,"And say<a class=""sup""><sup>sg </sup></a>, “Truth comes from your Lord. So whoever wills—let him believe, and whoever wills—let him disbelieve”. We have indeed prepared for the unjust a fire whose curtains have hemmed them in, and when they cry for relief, they are relieved with water like molten brass which scalds the faces. What a miserable drink, and what a bad place of rest!"
  18,30,"Indeed, those who have attained faith and have done righteous deeds…{1}—indeed, We do not waste the reward of whoever excels in work.",footnotes:1:This sentence is left open-ended; according Az-Zamakhshari its predicate is sign 31.
  18,31,"For those, there are the Gardens of Eden,rivers flowing beneath them. In it, they are{1}adorned with bracelets of gold and wear green garments of silk and brocade, reclining therein on couches. What a wonderful recompense, and what an excellent place of rest!",footnotes:1:A grammatical shift to present tense, which serves to create a vivid portrait of future events.
  18,32,"And set<a class=""sup""><sup>sg </sup></a>forth for them a parable of two men. To one of them We gave two gardens of grapevines, and We bordered them with palm-trees and We placed between them vegetation."
  18,33,"Each of the two gardens brought forth its crops in full and failed not in the least therein, and We caused a river to burst forth throughout them."
  18,34,"And thus he had riches{1}, so he said to his fellow as he conversed with him, “I am wealthier than you and greater in manpower.”",footnotes:1:The Arabic word used is thamarwhich can be pronounced as thumror thumuraccording to the majority of reciters, and in all cases it also means ‘produce’.
